Under California law, could a customer that was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by showing the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice of the spill and failed to have it cleaned for a half-hour because he was eating dinner?

A judge is not likely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s punitive damage claim. To state a claim that an award of punitive damages is justified a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant’s actions were committed with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result from the conduct, as well as showing that the conduct was despicable. Palmer will be able to argue that Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning a spill because multiple D&D customers were injured from slipping in the months prior to Palmer’s accident; and despite this knowledge he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer’s argument that Martin’s actions were despicable are less persuasive, but are still reasonable given the facts that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate actions to maintain the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009 at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne an employee of D&D Markets informed his manager, Paul Martin that there was an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne that he was on dinner break and “didn’t have time to deal with customer complaints.” At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in the year 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are examining whether to file a motion for partial summary against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud or malice.” Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct that intended to cause harm, or absent intent, the conduct must be “despicable” and committed with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others.” id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights when the defendant “was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences.” Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the class's main points of contention was the nature of Islam, specifically whether it was inherently hostile. I find this debate even more pertinent today. Looking back on events since 9/11, I've seen the U.S. media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an almost extreme tolerance for the religion. In 2001, it's unthinkable that a presidential candidate with a Muslim background, like Barak Obama, could have had a prominent political career.
The Prophet Muhammad's biography intrigued me because it seems to contradict his historical persona. From my knowledge of Muhammad's history, I believed he forced conversions, conquering tribes and imposing Islam. However, the biography portrays him as a martyred figure, misunderstood and humbled by others, instead of a conqueror. Gradually, people supposedly came to recognize the truth in his teachings.
Moreover, there are striking parallels between Jesus' teachings and Muhammad's miracles. For instance, both multiplied food to feed a large crowd. This style of writing suggests Muhammad was a humble prophet, needing no proof but embodying truth and miracles. This is problematic because it detracts from Jesus' miracle and life. It feels like they're appropriating Jesus' legacy through Muhammad.
The biography also contains stories aimed to prove 'witness' or self-conversions to Islam. However, many are third-party accounts, recounted through intermediaries, which I find dubious. While they intend to validate the stories, they actually diminish them.
What bothers me most is their portrayal of Muhammad as a godly, humble, wise, and gentle man. Historical accounts contradict this image, and I wonder if Muslims are aware of Muhammad's rise to power's true history.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus, as he held during his lifetime, were gradually left behind in the evolution of Christian thought that followed his passing. When we examine this historical trajectory in a broad sense, we notice a trend of Christianity drifting further and further from its origins. In today's world, we see an increasing awareness and a unprecedented progressive inclination. While traditional individuals persist and resist any thought that goes beyond what has been taught to them, this segment of society might not be large enough to sway the whole. Among Christians, a heightened historical understanding is expected to grow in the coming years. There will be a growing desire to differentiate the doctrines that were integrated into Christianity over time from the religion's actual founder's intentions. It may take decades or even centuries, but the reversal of this trend is inevitable: a progression back to its original form is on the horizon. A movement will emerge, fueled by a growing number of adherents, stripping away layers of doctrine, one by one, almost like rewinding the clock, until only the essence of what Jesus brought to humanity on behalf of God remains, before any other thinkers made such claims. This shift will sweep through the United States and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as if we were living during Jesus' time, solely following his teachings. The church as an institution will lead the way in this process, but because the theological clock will have been rewound, the vast diversity within Christendom will give way to increasing uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of every kind, we will see growing similarities rather than differences. Human history is filled with such reversals. For instance, Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later the empire became a Christian institution. Our country transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The coming great reversion in Christian history will unfold in the arena of the Christian religion, reversing history to rediscover its source, and undoing diversity in the process. The key to this process lies in reading Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime?
                If we delve deep into history, we find only Judaism, the theological foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were at Christianity's core by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was far from united; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

I firmly believe that The Jungle exposes the inherent greed and self-interest that lies deep within human nature. People are fundamentally driven to secure their own well-being and prosperity, rarely considering the plight of those beneath them. This theme is vividly illustrated through the owners and managers of the massive factories, who prioritize their company's growth and wealth above all else. They show utter disregard for any obstacles or the harm caused by their operations, as depicted by Upton Sinclair's words, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair paints a stark picture of the environmental destruction and health hazards resulting from their carelessness.

These owners and managers also demonstrate no concern for the employees who toil to enrich them. Their focus is solely on maximizing profits, as Sinclair puts it, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They subject their workers to harsh conditions and arbitrary layoffs without notice or compensation. During the time The Jungle was set, workers had little legal protection, enabling the managers and owners to exploit them with impunity.

The book doesn't explicitly state it, but the people who suffered and died in Packingtown were resigned to their miserable existence. There were no mechanisms to provide support or information to the workers. Unions formed to protect them often did more harm than good, lining their own pockets. The workers were trapped in a system where their well-being was secondary, and they were likened to slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or attitudes towards significant subjects. Some methods are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes several of these techniques in his novel, The Great Gatsby. He often combines an adjective and noun in an unconventional way to create a unique atmosphere around a subject. Additionally, he assigns symbolic meaning to colors and then employs these symbols to evoke emotions.

Fitzgerald uses this technique with various hues, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, he builds a specific meaning for white/gray and later uses that meaning to evoke certain feelings around important objects. The meaning Fitzgerald ascribes to white/gray is uniformity, with white representing a higher status and gray signifying something older, faded, or common.

He establishes this meaning early in the novel with frequent references to both colors. Daisy and Jordan are constantly depicted as “in white,” (8) and even Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party. The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick observes Gatsby’s lavish party: “The halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further emphasizes these colors by coloring everyday, unremarkable subjects in white and gray. Nick’s journey to work is described as “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), and even the names of partygoers on Nick’s schedule are now “gray names” (61). He also uses white and gray to describe mundane people or places, such as Jordan and Daisy’s “white girlhood” (19), the “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes, and the “gray” (26) Italian child on the train.

After establishing the significance of white/gray, Fitzgerald employs them to symbolize unimportance or uniformity. This technique begins with Daisy. After a prolonged absence of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster,” (74) making her seem less a character and more like a uniform object Gatsby desires. He reinforces this impression of Daisy’s uniformity with more descriptions of her in white, such as her “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18) and her “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s confrontation.

San Diego County boasts a rich agricultural landscape due to its mild and sunny climate, yielding a variety of crops such as tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The demand for organic community-supported agriculture is strong, with numerous local organizations boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation can attract government programs, improve habitat, and create opportunities for tours, educational programs, and additional revenue. While organic farming can enhance biodiversity and reduce chemical use, it requires more labor, management, and may have greater losses compared to conventional farming. Added benefits for wildlife, such as cover crop planting and strategic grazing, may also increase labor costs. Hence, the landowner may seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize profits and habitat quality.

The chosen parcel, near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This plan includes over a hundred plant and animal species, many endangered like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher, with some declining and potentially soon to be listed, such as burrowing owls.

This area has a rich history of Native American habitation, followed by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This land has been part of an original homestead and likely used for grazing and/or wood production over the years. The landowner selected this property after researching available government programs to offset costs and promote wildlife-friendly operations. As a model, the landowner considered an organic farm in the same region.

Every negotiation is deeply influenced by culture, which is as much about what it isn't as what it is. Culture isn't uniform, one-size-fits-all, or limited to national boundaries. Broad generalizations like "all Germans are punctual" or "all Mexicans are friendly" oversimplify reality. While general cultural insights can be beneficial, a savvy negotiator should focus on the specific cultural attitudes that shape the negotiation at hand. When encountering an unfamiliar culture, it's natural to compare it to our own, but it's crucial to adapt our approach rather than trying to impose our norms or judge. Accepting and working within cultural boundaries, especially when our bargaining power is weaker, can help navigate negotiations smoother.

Understanding a culture also means recognizing its history, prejudices, and values. Instead of dismissing or attempting to change a culture, a negotiator should embrace it, especially when negotiating in a foreign setting or a company with a distinct culture. Corporate culture varies widely, even within a single country. A company might prioritize long work hours or casualness, reflected in dress codes, communication styles, and hiring practices. Some companies encourage employee philanthropy, while others restrict it. American corporate culture alone showcases great diversity, from strict hierarchies to more laid-back environments. Even cultures that seem uniform from the outside may hide complex underlying dynamics.

Values are key to understanding a culture, as they reveal the "why" behind cultural behaviors. For instance, if a culture values consensus, a negotiator won't publicly humiliate their counterpart. If a culture values hard bargaining, a negotiator won't rush to settle. Before stepping into negotiations, it's essential to grasp the general cultural values. However, digging deeper into the personal qualities of your opponent can also provide valuable insights to make the negotiation more productive.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” This quote from Psalm 14 in the Christian Bible and St. Anselm’s initial argument about the existence of God share a common theme. Both St. Anselm and St. Thomas Aquinas argue for the same concept of God and we will compare their arguments to determine whose is stronger. We'll assume they both are correct about God's existence for simplicity, focusing on the God of the Bible. Both men bring valid points, but neither provides a complete basis for belief in God.

Let's start with St. Anselm’s approach. He argues that God's existence can be found within our own understanding, requiring no external evidence. His claim is that if God is within our comprehension, we cannot logically deny his existence. This idea is similar to faith, as it relies on accepting something without irrefutable proof.

St. Thomas Aquinas, however, believes that God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without faith. This method could help spread Christianity by persuading new converts with logic alone. Aquinas presents five logical arguments to support his claim: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument shows that the need for God is a logical necessity, similar to assembling a puzzle with missing pieces.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince destined to be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned worldly pursuits and attained enlightenment, his teachings giving rise to Buddhism, with the most traditional sect being Theravada Buddhism. Over the centuries, the religion has evolved, and this can be seen in practices like Sri Lanka's annual water-cutting ceremony, which Buddha never taught about. Even the religion's core beliefs have shifted over time due to both internal and external forces that can be either hostile or benign.

The United States of America and Mexico once had a longstanding rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893, with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848 being the peak of their conflict. The war resulted in the United States gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. This ongoing rivalry was characterized by disagreements over religion, culture, and tradition, as well as material interests. It is not uncommon for neighboring nations to have such rivalries, as they often share a border and thus have competing interests. This was true for the United States and Mexico, who unlike other Latin American nations, were perpetual rivals. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). This rivalry was not just about politics but also about religion, a common issue that has caused disputes between nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) observes that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy" (p.86). The rivalry between the United States and Mexico was a reflection of the ideological struggle between the English and Spanish, an inheritance from their colonial past that made friendly relations difficult to establish. Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during this period, most of which were about territorial issues and border raids. As Mexico became more dependent on the United States and American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention, the rivalry began to fade in the late 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, an illness I never knew existed suddenly disabled me, transforming my life irrevocably. As a nurse, I had chosen this profession to find the safety and security I lacked as a child, with the mantra "You'll always have work; people will always get sick" guiding my path. Despite my dreams of being a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing for the certainty it offered. Yet here I was, at 46, unable to work, and with no savings. After 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have nothing left that's truly mine. My life is a daily struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing is certain anymore, but I know one thing: I wouldn't have made it without the help of family and friends. When disaster strikes, we feel vulnerable, not strong.

My point is that life is full of emergencies, big and small. No guarantees exist, and some challenges are too great to face alone. We must stop relying solely on big government, moldy and falling apart. Instead, we should learn to trust each other, to help one another, and ask for help. In truth, rugged individualism didn't build our country; it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources that kept our forefathers going. Pioneers didn't cross the Rockies alone; they traveled in wagon trains.

So, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purifying tablets, and plastic sheeting for biological attacks. I have flashlights, batteries, candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have land and resources for a small farm, can or preserve your own food. A wood stove is a great idea, as long as you don't live in an apartment. But while you prepare, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve as they do? Are there any limits or barriers that shape their evolutionary path? Despite D'Arcy Thompson's 1917 statement that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this remains true today. Modern mathematical modeling has been applied to various aspects of mollusk shell formation through both development and evolution (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research explores how combining mathematical modeling with experimental studies can reveal the mechanisms behind the direction and scale of evolutionary change in Prunum. Using X-ray images, we identified quantitative parameters that we then used to model hypothetical and actual shell morphologies in the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). These models help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum. This approach is being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events within this group.

A shell can be visualized as a structure that winds through 360 degrees of space over time, with each loop or turn called a whorl, which spirals around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. Whorls grow at varying speeds, and the line separating each whorl is called a suture. The largest whorl is the body whorl, and the spire consists of all the whorls except the last. The apex is the top of the spire, and the base is the opposite end. The aperture is the opening through which the animal exits its shell.

Shells can be viewed from various angles: apical (top view), basal (bottom view), apertural (side view with the aperture facing the viewer), and abapertural (side view with the aperture away from the viewer). The "usual" orientation is the apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first view the shell from an apical perspective and locate the first suture. Draw a line to divide the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl if necessary.

A shell can also be seen as a series of apertures that travel through space and time as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using the center of each whorl's aperture, as well as its horizontal and vertical radius.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. By varying parameters, we can modify the mollusk's shell development.

The neonatal and infant mortality rate in Indonesia has remained relatively unchanged over the past decade. Despite the country's progress towards meeting several Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, improvements in child and maternal health are significantly lagging behind. The reasons for this are multifaceted, suggesting a need to bolster the overall health system rather than focusing solely on specific programs.

Indonesia has seen an increase in births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complicated pregnancies, leading to high maternal death rates due to hemorrhage. This improvement is somewhat misleading, indicating that much more work is needed.

There has also been a decline in the proportion of children under five years old with diarrheal cases treated by health professionals, and data on postnatal care is incomplete but shows low rates of care across the country.

Cesarean-section rates remain low at around 4%, with a notable disparity between urban (7%) and rural (2%) settings, highlighting issues of equity in healthcare access. Another access concern is the 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting that the poor struggle more to access healthcare services, possibly due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering how to address these issues, one must ask whether Indonesia should focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the entire health system. While program-specific interventions have targeted, manageable objectives and can generate faster results, they can also lead to funding and human resource imbalances, as well as uncoordinated service duplication.

Victorian novels are often marked by their meticulous attention to detail and concentration on the aristocracy of the era. However, two works that deviate from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels infuse an element of mystery and embrace of the peculiar, traits uncommon in Victorian literature, thereby enhancing the characters' depth and unveiling their motivations and emotions.

“A swarm of bewildering and perplexing thoughts now assailed his mind. He seemed to be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were furiously arguing. Even their voices echoed in his ears, and when he focused on himself, he realized he was speaking to them as well. Suddenly, he recoiled at the sound of gunshots; and there arose loud cries and screeches; lights flashed before his eyes, and all was chaos and commotion, as if an unseen force was hurriedly carrying him away. Throughout these rapid visions, a constant, uneasy awareness of pain gnawed at him, wearing and tormenting him endlessly.” (Dickens, 220)

The novels employ this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, with varying content and function. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often illuminate some aspect of Oliver’s psyche, revealing his innermost struggles and understanding of the events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he relives the experience as if in a dream, grappling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events, as well as his dire straits, evident in his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself engulfs him, numbing his senses so he doesn't notice the “unseen hand” that bears him away; he experiences his despair again, removed from the initial shock of pain, now a constant presence linked with fear rather than surprise. The question arises: Whose will brought about his misfortune, for it certainly wasn't his own? This shooting underscores Oliver's lack of control over anything, even in life-threatening situations. It suggests a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if Fagin had broken him, forcing him to accept this despair and influencing his ability to react. For otherwise, it could be assumed Oliver would at least attempt to save himself.

“The day passed – day! It was gone as soon as it came – and night returned, long yet fleeting, with its dreadful silence and swift passage.” (Brontë, 42)

I worked in an after school program tutoring elementary students a couple of years ago. I did my best to help them, but my strengths lay in English and reading. One day, an instructor asked me to assist a boy named Adrian, who was struggling with his reading. Something didn't feel right; his issues were peculiar. He could pronounce some letters perfectly while others were off, even though he spoke English flawlessly. His background was Latino, but he understood English like a native. We kept trying, but when his mother walked in, everything changed. She communicated only in Spanish, and my Spanish skills were limited. Then it hit me: Adrian could read well, but he didn't know the English alphabet very well. I'm not sure if this revelation helped him much, but I hope he's improved.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier problem in schools, especially in California. It's not always as apparent as we think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can be a challenge. Everyone agrees this is an issue, but what do we do about it? For Adrian, the solution was simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. But for children who barely speak English, the solution is complex. There's no single answer. Combining dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, or other methods is key.

Firstly, the dual language system is promising. Benefits extend beyond Spanish-speaking children; all children can benefit. Children in two-way bilingual programs often outperform their peers academically. Many fear this idea, thinking it wastes resources and doesn't help the majority. This is incorrect. If implemented widely, all children could profit. But how? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual is unrealistic. Instead, we could have bilingual aids or tutors to support the dual language system.

From our earliest days, many of us are told there's something greater than ourselves, something we cannot comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school or temple, while others look inward for answers. Some readily accept the faiths passed down by our parents, while others reject them entirely, believing there's nothing beyond our personal worldview. We may adopt one set of values, only to later embrace another. Regardless of the path we choose, we strive to define ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We search for a light to guide us out of darkness and into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said in response to my question about his favorite bird. We sat on our porch, listening to the rain hammer on the tin roof while we shared a cigarette. The gutters sent the rain cascading down, drowning the plants at the porch's edge. He stared out into the rain, his gaze both searching and recalling something. He had grown thinner, his clothes loose on his frame, and his hair sparser. He kept his eyes on the rain, avoiding my gaze. I felt isolated, apprehensive, and unable to discuss my fear of losing him, as speaking about it would only make it more real. I embraced him, sat back down, and moved my chair closer, gazing out at the falling rain of the June evening alongside him.

My father passed away in December, mere weeks after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his suffering, but kept him alive longer than the doctors expected. I could not fathom the worth of this extension when he only endured more pain. What kind of god would do this? I thought to myself. Alone at night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I believed, He had stopped listening long ago.

I had not wanted to witness my father's transition from this life to another. So I did not. I could not watch the life that gave me mine as it ended. I wanted to remember my father the way he lived, not the way he died. Besides, I knew my father better than anyone else, and I was sure he would not wish for his only child to be a witness to his passing. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one reached out to me.

The classic "Gothic Novel" is a intriguing blend of "old" and "new," as Ian Watt asserts in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This literary mode has been critiqued and celebrated, with critics dismissing its depth and praising its "terrible sublime" qualities (Burke). The original Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, merged "old" romantic elements with "new" literary techniques to establish the proto-Gothic genre, offering a fresh approach to storytelling. Walpole incorporated classical theatrical elements and "new" mimetic nature in his novel, presenting what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily from medieval gothic theater, architecture, and customs. Despite the word "gothic" being used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods, it was seen as archaic by many in Walpole's time, contrasting with the "modern" societal and literary advancements. This fusion of the more theatrical "Gothic" style and the intimate novel format, allowing readers a deeper insight into character psychology, has kept Gothic literature relevant for centuries, making it simultaneously antiquated and fresh for readers far removed from its origins.

One of the most prominent themes in Gothic novels is chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, training a proper knight, is retained and transformed in Walpole's The Castle of Otranto. Gothic authors embraced chivalry because it epitomized the ideal knight—brave, honorable, and skilled. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous period, may have felt that societal morality and inherent goodness had declined. This is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits. Frederic is described thus:

The description of him includes various chivalric images; Frederic is a prince, has endured tragedy, and is presumed to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-come Gothic trope of excess (66).

The art of supply chain management involves navigating the flow of goods from the moment a customer places an order, through various stages like raw materials, production, and distribution, until the product reaches the customer. This concept was first coined by Keith Oliver, a consultant, in 1982. He described the comprehensive process of planning, executing, and controlling the supply chain operations to swiftly and effectively meet customer needs. The supply chain management comprises six crucial elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These elements are utilized by business managers to deliver top-notch customer service.

Production is the cornerstone of the supply chain process. It sets the foundation for the entire journey. At this stage, managers must determine the when, why, where, and how of production. To gauge customer wants, they turn to the market, which is the primary indicator of demand. Once the market's demands are understood, managers can decide which products to produce and in what quantities. Subsequently, they choose the optimal location for production, considering factors like volume and quality, keeping customer needs in mind. Production is a pivotal step, and meticulous planning is essential. Even minor details can significantly impact a company's efficiency and expenses. For instance, my previous experiences at Wal-Mart and Target taught me the importance of clear processes and layouts. These retail giants have detailed manuals for every aspect of their operation, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, ensuring smooth operations and clear expectations.

The next key element is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions about the core capabilities of a facility and selecting outsourcing partnerships. A company may have multiple divisions for a single product, each with its unique equipment and workforce. The manager must choose the most suitable division for each part of the production process. Outsourcing is often employed to achieve velocity, which means providing quality, flexibility, and cost-effectiveness.

The sign reads something both chilling and perplexing: "Hitler is alive in Burma." Ellen Page, the star from Juno, stands alone on a city street, a piece of cardboard held above her head, on which she has scrawled her message with a Sharpie. Burma, now known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian nation governed by a ruthless military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup d’état. In 2007, protests began, led by numerous Burmese monks, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. The gatherings, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution" after the monks' robes, initially started peacefully but soon turned violent, with the military invading and destroying monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were jailed, and a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was murdered on September 27th, 2007, simply for documenting the protests. While the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army, claims that thousands have been killed.

This is not a new phenomenon. Throughout history, regimes have suppressed dissent and asserted total control over their citizens. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule, Japanese emperors are seen as gods, and even our current president, George W. Bush, is rumored to have weekly chats with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Notable examples of this oppression include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to challenge the government's authoritarian rule, resulting in an estimated 2,000-3,000 deaths as per some sources. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups and the Rwandan government systematically killed Tutsis and political moderates, is another horrifying example. Hitler's Third Reich saw a systematic persecution and murder of Jews across multiple countries.

The sign, "Hitler is alive in Burma," stands as a stark reminder of the continuing struggle against tyranny and oppression worldwide.

Duke Ellington's enduring legacy in jazz is heavily grounded in his mastery of both orchestration and composition. His subtle piano presence in many pieces allows him to highlight the unique talents of each band member, crafting a framework where soloists can freely improvise. Ellington’s genius lies in his ability to create intricate musical phrases that showcase individual instruments and collectively emphasize the tone of the orchestra. This skill has enabled him to produce some of the most groundbreaking works in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington’s innovative use of the human voice, likening it to a jazz instrument. A prime example of this is "Creole Love Call," an early work where Ellington employs a call-and-response dynamic between the voice and reed instruments. This twelve-bar blues piece, comprising six choruses, illustrates his talent for complementing soloists and adding rich layers of tone color. The first chorus features a voice that starts smoothly and transitions to a rougher sound, while the fifth chorus culminates in a climactic high register call-and-response. The trombone's dissonant ending adds a playful touch. Ellington's use of voice to enrich the piece sets a tone that runs through his entire career.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington continues to exhibit his prowess in tight orchestration and tone color. A call-and-response between "Bubber" Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing seamlessly harmonizes the vocal elements of Miley’s playing with the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" further exemplifies this, with Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone introducing the melody, showcasing Ellington’s skill at integrating individual instruments into a cohesive whole.

She had always felt an unfulfilled longing. Since she was 14, this desire had refused to be satiated. Now, at 17, she realized she wanted a companion more than a possession, but no one appealed to her. She wondered why this happened to her and tried to figure it out but found no satisfactory answers. So, she lived life, questioning her desires constantly.

A typical day at home was peaceful with her parents, who were calm and rarely argued. They only argued about her asserting her independence. She was the daughter of calm parents but had a fun-loving personality that made her popular. Today, however, was not peaceful. As she looked for inspiration, she heard her mother's scream from the kitchen. Running in, she found her mother in pain, having fallen off a stool while reaching for a vase. "Ow," her mother kept saying with short breaths. "Take me to the hospital," she rushed out. Her daughter quickly carried her to the car, grateful for her strength, and drove to the hospital.

The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness, but her mind was occupied with helping her mother. She carried her quickly to a bed and called for doctors. Her mother had fallen from a stool trying to grab a vase.

This study aimed to demonstrate that sticking to the “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as indicated by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke-related death. The aMed diet is a version of the Med diet with increased intake of plant foods (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (over saturated fats), and fish, and decreased consumption of animal products and saturated fats. It allows for moderate alcohol intake.

Previous research has shown that adhering to the Med diet is inversely related to the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial found it to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the total-to-high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. Prior studies, however, did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, with no history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study. This study involved 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Every year from 1984 to 2004, the researchers computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (FFQs) to assess nutrient intake in the previous year. Over 95% of nurses continued to participate over the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation, and reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Each FFQ also calculated body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize individual random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score were calculated from repeated FFQs (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between aMed scores and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 cases of incident CHD, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths were found. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States was hit by a severe financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market crashed, and numerous major corporations crumbled. This economic downturn persists to this day, so we must consider: how did this crisis unfold, and how can we prevent it from happening again? Simply put, the financial crisis was sparked by self-serving political decisions that forced banks and firms to issue risky sub-prime loans within an already unstable financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to back and bundle these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks found themselves short on capital reserves, passing the turmoil onto the bundled mortgages they had sold and throughout the economy.
The seeds of this financial crisis were sown in 1999 under the Clinton administration, as the president sought to secure a second term. To boost his popularity, he relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income individuals and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its impressive profit growth.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences: “But this government-subsidized corporation could face trouble in an economic downturn, leading to a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As discussed earlier, ill-advised lending would certainly cause the economy to collapse.
Many factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin, including the innovative and complex mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs were extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, further interweaving the economy with the housing market. This overextension made both households and financial markets highly vulnerable to even minor fluctuations in housing prices. Ultimately, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities suffered severe losses. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, representing around 30% of the USA’s GDP. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were transformed into commercial banks under intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That dreadful section of your tale where you, as a writer, attempt to spread your wings and take flight, captivating your audience with your spellbinding words. Or the part where your readers yawn and hit the "Back" button while muttering your name. Dr. Merlin has been known to hurl her keyboard at the screen when she finds herself mired in the muck of Too Much Information, and it's never in the enjoyable way.

Exposition is your nemesis.

My dear readers already know the cardinal rule of writing, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still finds herself entangled in lengthy passages where not much happens, or worse, where too much does. Exposition is that little demon sitting on your shoulder, whispering in your ear to get the backstory out of the way to get to the good stuff (not to be confused with the other demon urging you to spill every single detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means informing the audience what happened, usually in basic prose. In film, exposition occurs when one character dumps a bunch of information on another, akin to "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Consider this example: You're reading a story, and you're told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, that they wed in a grand ceremony, and that her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to consume two pages, during which both characters only exchange a couple of lines. You would expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showcasing his love for his wife through his words and actions, and to reveal the heroine's deep affection and the transformative impact of his presence in her life (especially if the story later states that this was the case). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to empathize with his fate and to connect with the heroine.

In essence, you'd expect substance to be added to the bare bones of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you must provide that substance. (*dwells on the metaphor, sighs, presses on*) Sometimes, you may be tempted to hurry past certain aspects. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to serve in the Air Force, now works as the night manager of a gas station, was married twice with no children, loves fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I caught two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was "live" on NBC 4 this morning. The top story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife. They didn't mention her name, but his was Shad Hostettler. His mugshot showed a stern face. They spent only two minutes on this story, which seemed adequate for the ongoing investigation. The next story was an early morning shooting in the Sharon Woods area, where a young man named Travis Buyers, 18, was critically injured. No arrests were made, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story felt short, and I suspect it was due to the victim being a minority. I've noticed over the years that minority crime victims are often overlooked by the media compared to white victims.
The following story concerned a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details of the incident were provided, and it was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had caused the damage. Crime-Stoppers was offering a five-thousand dollar reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.
They also aired a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The suspect was described as a dark-skinned black man, about six-foot tall and weighing around 150 pounds. They devoted an unusual amount of time to emphasizing his race and the darkness of his skin. The last story was about a convicted Texas drug kingpin named Rene Rodriguez. He had been sentenced to 300 months in prison (which I believe they thought sounded harsher than 25 years). They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but I don't think that was relevant to the story.

There is a profound and unyielding connection between brothers; a bond that is unbreakable and irrevocable. Within this bond lies a complex tapestry of emotions, including love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers understand each other in a way that no one else can, and they see their own reflection in the eyes of their sibling. The true nature of this bond becomes evident when a situation reaches its climax, whether it be for good or ill. When these emotions are laid bare, they come at a great cost. One must confront the consequences that arise from this fraternal connection. When you look into your brother’s eyes, you see not only your own reflection but also your true self, unfiltered by the opinions of others. Your actions and their outcomes define your character. In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers delve into this theme, along with the intense emotions it engenders. Set against a lush, vivid backdrop, the two embark on a futile journey. In the culminating scene, bitterness and pride clash, and only one brother survives. The theme is explored through the direct portrayal of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator’s perspective, which reveals the protagonist’s complex feelings and his view of the world, both of which greatly influence his actions.

The protagonist’s actions are driven by a single overriding emotion: pride. From their first outing to their final, tragic excursion, the protagonist resents Doodle. He desired a brother who could take part in his adventures, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp. He wanted a companion for races to Horsehead Landing and to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. However, Doodle’s condition, born with a weak heart, made such activities unlikely. This dashed the young protagonist’s dreams, and he even considered suffocating Doodle with a pillow. Yet, when Doodle smiled at him, the protagonist’s heart softened, showing his love for his brother was stronger than his initial resentment. This deep bond, once laid bare, is evident in the protagonist’s actions and the consequences they bring.

The human brain is a complex information-processing system that has evolved with technology, changing its metaphors from a wax tablet to a computer. Remember, these metaphors, while useful, can lead to misunderstandings as you learn about the brain.

Information processing begins with sensory organs converting physical stimuli into electrochemical signals. The brain transforms this sensory information through bottom-up and top-down processing. In bottom-up processing, simple details like color and orientation help you recognize a box in a picture. Top-down processing speeds this up by using the initial decisions made from bottom-up processing to identify it as a black box. Attention filters then decide what information is important, like your name in a noisy room, while filtering out less crucial details like individual blades of grass.

For information to be processed, it must first be stored. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is encoded into these memories in various ways, such as how a word looks, sounds, or means. Working memory, which stores information briefly, is maintained by electrical signals looping through specific neurons. Long-term memory is believed to be maintained by the structure of certain proteins.

How knowledge is organized in the brain varies by model. Some are based on how people retrieve memories, others on computer science or neurophysiology. The semantic network model, for instance, suggests that concepts are nodes linked by relatedness, like how "chair" is linked to "table" and "wooden."

Aldous Huxley takes a critical stance on the looming threats of technology and the capitalist system that undergirds it, painting a dystopian future in his novel Brave New World. The society in this world values collective happiness over individuality, and citizens are conditioned from birth to prioritize immediate gratification. The people are essentially pawns in a grand game orchestrated by the World Controller, who dictates their ideology. Examining the novel through a Marxist lens, one can see Huxley's concern with the development of these systems. Terms like homogeneity and reification reinforce the idea that the novel critiques the flaws of the emerging economic system of Huxley's time.

Capitalism is satirized through the concept of false consciousness, a Marxist idea. It prevents the common people from understanding their true economic ties to other classes, as they are mainly focused on their own advancement. This is due to the ideological control of the proletariat and laborers, evident in the conditioning of people in Brave New World. Lower classes like Deltas and Gammas have no will of their own; they are conditioned to consume, spend, and indulge through hypnopædia. This manipulation is carried out by the World Controller, while hegemony, where a dominant group controls the rest, is also evident. Lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, unknowingly supporting the capitalist structure. The upper classes, while aware, do little to challenge the system. The interactions between social classes, such as the superficial relationships and the lack of genuine emotion, highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism. In this world, relationships are shallow, with men reducing women to their physical appeal and women openly discussing their encounters. This indicates the socioeconomic impact of capitalism, as each class accepts their place in the hierarchy and maintains their obedience.

I have been a student at University Park for almost three years, or roughly five semesters. Navigating campus can be a genuine challenge for many, including myself. My freshman year, I was assigned a room in East Halls, which was about as far east as you could get without leaving campus, aside from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Commutes to classes in far-off locations like the Willard Building, near the heart of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather was less than ideal, as it often is in State College. An alumni, only slightly older than myself, shared that just a few years ago, the East Halls dorms were isolated by vast, unused land. Now, that empty space has been transformed into sports fields, new structures like the Creamery and health services building, and apartment complexes. As our campus continues to grow, traversing from one place to another becomes increasingly challenging. So, what's the best solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's bicycles. But a bike alone won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed with bikers in mind.
A friend of mine recently resumed cycling after several years. He mentioned he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are fantastic," he said, "for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride, but it’s the only way to go." Beyond the physical benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of exertion can get you 30 miles or more. Like many undergrads, I now live off campus, as far from the campus center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was buying a bike. Every day, I attend a class in Thomas Building, a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce this travel time to just 5 minutes, provided I pedal fast enough. The only downside is that Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas from my house, isn’t always the easiest road to travel on, whether by bike or foot. While walking has its merits, I simply don’t have the time. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only option, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my daily commute. That’s over two and a half hours each week. Plus, the additional time to walk to and from other classes, appointments, and so on would be more time than I can spare.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists.
